010/26\nCategory: AD Airport Operations\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-22 20:46 - 2026-05-25 08:30\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, and OIAW, which are operational from sunrise to sunset. All previous permissions are suspended for all operators, and new permission must be requested from the CAA for operation of civil IFR passenger flights on these airports.\nRaw NOTAM shown:\nA1010/26 NOTAMR A0799/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605222046 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART\nOF TEHRAN FIR ARE CLSD\nEXCEPT OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, AND OIAW THAT ARE\nOPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS,\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FM CAA FOR OPRATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS ON THESE AIRPORTS.\nPage status text included: NOTAM Inactive.\n\n[defendant] DX-S2 A1015/26 expanded operational exceptions\nSource: Notamify OIIX NOTAM page\nURL: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/67435351-52f9-4d17-8f4c-497a21dd94bf\nRetrieved: 2026-06-19T23:59:20Z\nTitle shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed airports, which are operational HJ.\nNOTAM identifier: A1015/26\nCategory: AD Airport Operations\nPeriod of applicability shown: UTC 2026-05-23 18:21 - 2026-05-25 08:30\nInterpretation shown: All airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW, OIFM, OITL, OISR and OIAM, which are operational from sunrise to sunset (HJ). All previous permissions are suspended for all operators. New permission must be requested from Iran CAA for civil IFR passenger flights.\nRaw NOTAM shown:\nA1015/26 NOTAMR A1010/26\nQ)OIIX/QFALC/IV/NBO/A/000/999/\nA)OIIX B)2605231821 C)2605250830EST\nE)REF NOTAM  A0796/26, ALL AIRPORTS IN WEST PART OF TEHRAN FIR\nARE CLSD EXCEPT:\nOITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW,OIFM, OITL,\nOISR AND OIAM\nTHAT ARE OPERATIONAL FM SUNRISE TO SUNSET (HJ).\nALL PREVIOUS PERMISSIONS ARE SUSPENDED FOR ALL OPERATORS.\nNEW PERMISSION SHALL BE REQUESTED FOR OPERATION OF\nCIVIL IFR PASSENGER FLIGHTS FM IRAN CAA.\nPage status text included: NOTAM Inactive.\n\n[defendant] DX-S3 Reported operational listed airports\nSource: Indian Express\nURL: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\nRetrieved: 2026-06-19T23:59:40Z\nHeadline: Iran shuts western airspace as US weighs fresh strikes; Rubio in Delhi flags 'progress' in Tehran talks\nByline/date shown: Express Global Desk; first published May 23, 2026 at 09:05 PM IST; 6 min read May 23, 2026 09:23 PM IST.\nRelevant captured text:\nIran has temporarily closed the airspace over its western half from May 22 to May 25, suspending all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX), as Washington weighs a fresh round of military strikes and Pakistani and Qatari mediators race to revive stalled US-Iran talks.\nThe Iranian Civil Aviation Authority issued a Notice to Airmen (NOTAM) — OIIX A1010/26 — on Friday, May 22, ordering the shutdown of all airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR, effective immediately and valid until May 25, the Gulf News reported.\nOnly eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas. Even at these, flights are restricted to daylight hours from sunrise to sunset, and airlines must obtain fresh per-flight approval from the Civil Aviation Authority, according to the NOTAM.\nFlight-tracking data shows commercial aircraft already rerouting away from western Iranian airspace, with multiple airlines avoiding the corridor entirely.\nThe article describes the closure as connected to anticipated military action and stalled US-Iran talks, not weather. It states the new NOTAM formalizes the most extensive restrictions in weeks.\n\n[defendant] DX-S4 Market rule requiring broad/general closure\n# Market page record\n\nOfficial event URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by\nOfficial May 24 market URL: https://polymarket.com/event/iran-closes-its-airspace-by/iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\nCaptured API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-event.json\nCaptured May 24 API file: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCaptured event page file: source-captures/polymarket-page-and-api-extract.txt\nCaptured May 24 page file or error: source-captures/polymarket-gamma-market-may-24.json\nCapture time: 2026-05-24T01:44:04Z\n\n## Event\n\n- event id: 438327\n- ticker/slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by / iran-closes-its-airspace-by\n- title: Iran closes its airspace by...?\n- event createdAt: 2026-05-01T16:11:36.585944Z\n- event creationDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431549Z\n- event startDate: 2026-05-01T18:22:49.431559Z\n- event endDate: 2026-05-31T00:00:00Z\n- event active: True\n- event closed: False\n- event volume at capture: 34658537.51144401\n\n## May 24 market\n\n- market id: 2241873\n- slug: iran-closes-its-airspace-by-may-24\n- question: Iran closes its airspace by May 24?\n- groupItemTitle: May 24\n- conditionId: 0x4ba348328e4d4ddee9e6734c9a369b2e8138611651f9f6dc8f59dea51df6c734\n- questionID: 0x30ebd10971cc044380ce6495e791828e9e0291fbb48550ca8be42149e1982791\n- createdAt: 2026-05-12T15:03:45.641355Z\n- startDate: 2026-05-12T15:08:30.267422Z\n- endDate: 2026-05-24T00:00:00Z\n- endDateIso: 2026-05-24\n- active: True\n- closed: False\n- acceptingOrders: True\n- umaResolutionStatus: disputed\n- umaResolutionStatuses: [\"proposed\", \"disputed\", \"proposed\", \"disputed\"]\n- outcomes: [\"Yes\", \"No\"]\n- outcomePrices: [\"0.157\", \"0.843\"]\n- lastTradePrice: 0.16\n- bestBid/bestAsk: 0.15 / 0.164\n- updatedAt: 2026-05-24T01:35:13.748834Z\n- volume at capture: 8289170.735521075\n\n## Rule text\n\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if Iran initiates a major closure of its airspace, that is not solely due to weather conditions, by the listed date, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to “No”.\n\nA “major closure” is defined as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region. Limited cancellations, delays, or other partial closures will not qualify. Limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting (e.g. exceptions for certain flights pre-approved by the Iranian Civil Aviation Authority may be permitted).\n\nAny non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two of the following airports will qualify: Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA), Mehrabad Airport (THR), Mashhad International Airport (MHD), Shiraz International Airport (SYZ), or Isfahan International Airport (IFN).\n\nQualifying previous examples include the January 2026 total closure of Iranian airspace except to international flights with express governmental permission (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iran-shuts-airspace-most-flights-flightradar24-says-2026-01-14/) and the April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace (https://www.reuters.com/world/middle-east/iranian-airports-cancel-flights-until-monday-morning-2024-04-14/). Non-qualifying examples include the January 27, 2026 partial closure of Iranian airspace around the Strait of Hormuz (https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iran-issues-airspace-notice-for-military-drills-near-strait-of-hormuz/3812508) and the January 25 - April 25, 2026 VFR (Visual Flight Rules) flights suspension which did not broadly close commercial aviation in a qualifying region (https://www.intellinews.com/iran-suspends-general-aviation-and-vfr-flights-in-new-airspace-directive-421997/).\n\nWarnings, No-Fly-Zones, or other flight restrictions imposed by airlines or countries other than Iran will not be sufficient for a “Yes” resolution.\n\nAirspace closures which occur solely due to weather conditions will not qualify.\n\nThe primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n## Notes for arbitration\n\nThe proposition tracks the rule text, not the platform-resolution question. The operative elements are: (1) Iran initiated the closure; (2) the closure was not solely weather-related; (3) the closure occurred by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET; (4) the closure was a major closure, defined by the rule as a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region; or a non-weather complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports; and (5) the primary sources are official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\n\n\nSubmitted evidence:\n[plaintiff arguments] Notamify capture of OIIX A1010/26 raw NOTAM (ev_a95b8d7e6e97_submitted-evidence-01-plaintiff-a95b8d7e6e97)\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/693f2d0f-54d3-433b-8128-49f5475ba269\nSHA-256: `a95b8d7e6e97fa3e3ce64d2dbd0386a2e9cd33cc24d601a9d0a01f396d661025`\nBytes: 1286\nRelevance: Primary-like NOTAM text for Iran/Tehran FIR airport closure effective May 22-May 25, 2026; proves scope, timing, exceptions, CAA permission requirement, and non-weather aviation restriction source chain.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Notamify capture of OIIX A1015/26 superseding NOTAM (ev_ecbf01d69176_submitted-evidence-02-plaintiff-ecbf01d69176)\nSource: https://notamify.com/notams/OIIX/67435351-52f9-4d17-8f4c-497a21dd94bf\nSHA-256: `ecbf01d69176ce74c29122ea30dcf33188fcb3525efdf32b34308bf7f99c9552`\nBytes: 1238\nRelevance: Shows the closure remained in force past the May 24 ET deadline after A1015/26 replaced A1010/26, with expanded exception list and continued CAA permission requirement.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Indian Express May 23 report on Iran western airspace closure (ev_a6be31686c80_submitted-evidence-03-plaintiff-a6be31686c80)\nSource: https://indianexpress.com/article/world/us-news/iran-closes-airspace-trump-cancels-plans-us-military-strikes-rubio-india-10704692/\nSHA-256: `a6be31686c80176d9d7195f76281647eb9a9d9b39b77a59b0b8e3d3ddbf8afa6`\nBytes: 1759\nRelevance: Credible reporting corroborating the NOTAM, CAA attribution, affected airports including listed market airports, operational limits, timing, and non-weather/security context.\n\n[plaintiff arguments] Arab Times May 23 report on Iran CAA western Tehran FIR restrictions (ev_098dc1dc0d2d_submitted-evidence-04-plaintiff-098dc1dc0d2d)\nSource: https://www.arabtimesonline.com/news/iran-suspends-flight-permissions-restricts-western-airspace-access/\nSHA-256: `098dc1dc0d2db3d30476992b3689d9a3ec6bcfb67085da015bc7ab644ebb85d4`\nBytes: 1224\nRelevance: Corroborates Iranian CAA attribution, May 22-May 25 timing, limited airport exceptions, suspension of prior permissions, fresh approval requirement, and security/non-weather context.\n\nTechnical reports:\n[plaintiff] Evidence search and weight ledger\nSearches targeted OIIX A1010/26, A1015/26, Iranian CAA attribution, May 22-May 25 timing, and adverse partial-closure issues. Direct official CAA custody was not captured; the strongest preserved source is raw NOTAM text from Notamify, corroborated by Indian Express and Arab Times reports. The airport lists in reporting are not perfectly identical to the raw NOTAM, so the plaintiff relies on the major-region closure path rather than the two-listed-airport complete-suspension path.\n\n[defendant] Defense Source And Scope Analysis\nRead all new plaintiff exhibits. The decisive source-chain problem is not timing or non-weather context but scope: the raw NOTAMs are third-party Notamify captures categorized as AD Airport Operations and focused on airport closures with many daylight operational exceptions and fresh CAA approvals. They do not directly prove a general suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from a major Iranian airspace region, and the reports confirm continuing limited operations at several important airports.\n\nCall submit_council_vote with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated.\nKeep the rationale brief: no more than three sentences.\n\nCouncil API instructions:\nYou are a council member. Decide the proposition from the admitted record.\nYou may examine admitted evidence through read-only tools when exact bytes, metadata, or exhibit contents matter.\nDo not search the web, introduce new facts, create new evidence, or upload evidence.\nWhen ready, call submit_council_vote exactly once with vote=demonstrated or vote=not_demonstrated and a concise rationale.\n","state":"ready","status":"ready","tools":[{"description":"Return the current visible arbitration record for this council member.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"get_case","read_only":true},{"description":"List visible immutable record evidence.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{},"type":"object"},"name":"list_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Return metadata and read limits for one visible evidence item.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"}},"required":["evidence_id"],"type":"object"},"name":"stat_evidence","read_only":true},{"description":"Read a bounded byte range from one visible evidence item as base64.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"evidence_id":{"type":"string"},"length":{"minimum":1,"type":"integer"},"offset":{"minimum":0,"type":"integer"}},"required":["evidence_id","offset","length"],"type":"object"},"name":"read_evidence_range","read_only":true},{"description":"Submit one council vote for the current deliberation opportunity.","input_schema":{"additionalProperties":false,"properties":{"rationale":{"type":"string"},"vote":{"enum":["demonstrated","not_demonstrated"],"type":"string"}},"required":["vote","rationale"],"type":"object"},"name":"submit_council_vote","read_only":false}],"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":false,"deadline":"2026-06-20T00:26:35.631444415Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C6","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C6","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":886651,"role_id":"council","turn_number":14},"wait":{"reason":"ready","state_version":18,"version":33}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"wait_for_opportunity"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1781914308986},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Okay, I need to process this AAR case arb-ex11a-20260619235218. Let's start by understanding the current state. The user called aar_wait_for_opportunity with an empty args and got a response saying \"state: ready\", with all the details like prompt, turn info, limits, etc.\n\nNow, the task is to review the arbitration record and admitted evidence, then submit a vote. The vote must be either \"demonstrated\" or \"not_demonstrated\" with a concise rationale.\n\nFirst, I need to understand the case. The proposition is whether Iran initiated a major airspace closure by May 24, 2026. The rule defines a \"major closure\" as either a broad closure of commercial flights in a major Iranian airspace region (with limited exceptions allowed) or a complete suspension at two listed airports.\n\nLooking at the evidence:\n\n- PX-1 (market rule) defines the criteria clearly. The key points are:\n  - Major closure: broad suspension of flights transit, arrive, depart from Iranian airspace/major region. Or complete suspension at two listed airports.\n  - Limited exceptions don't disqualify a broad closure, but partial closures like delays or limited cancellations do not qualify.\n  - Examples: Qualifying include Jan 2026 total closure, April 2024 western closure; non-qualifying are partial closures like Strait of Hormuz restrictions or VFR suspension.\n\n- PX-2 and PX-3: NOTAMs from Notamify. A1010/26 and A1015/26 show Iran's CAA closed \"all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR\" except some operational daylight airports with fresh permissions. These were active through the deadline.\n\n- PX-4 and PX-5: Indian Express and Arab Times reports corroborating the NOTAMs, mentioning closure of western half/sector, limited airports operating daylight, fresh approvals. They attribute it to military/security tensions, not weather.\n\nDefendant's arguments (DX-1 to DX-S4) focus on the scope. The NOTAMs are categorized as \"AD Airport Operations\" and only close airports with exceptions. They argue it's not a broad closure of the airspace region itself—since some airports remain operational (including key listed ones like Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini), it's a partial restriction with exceptions, not a general suspension of all flights in a major region.\n\nThe plaintiff argues the west part of Tehran FIR is a major region, and the NOTAM's language of \"all airports closed\" (with limited exceptions) meets the definition as a broad closure. The rule says limited exceptions don't disqualify, and the April 2024 western closure is a prior example.\n\nSo the crux is: does \"all airports in the west part of Tehran FIR are closed except listed operational ones\" count as a \"major closure of a major Iranian airspace region\" under the market's definition? Or is it a partial closure?\n\nKey quotes from the rule: \"broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region. A qualifying closure must apply generally to flights across Iran or a major Iranian airspace region.\"\n\nIn the NOTAM, the closure is described as airport operations being closed, but the exception list includes specific airports. However, the market's examples: April 2024's western airspace closure is a positive example. The current case's closure in West Tehran FIR is also regional.\n\nBut the defendant says: the NOTAM is categorized as \"airport operations,\" not FIR-wide airspace closure. But the rule covers \"commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from... a major Iranian airspace region.\" Closing airports in a region would affect those flights. The question is whether the region is \"major.\"\n\nThe Tehran FIR is a Flight Information Region, which is a significant area. Western part of Tehran FIR being closed would impact commercial flights in that region. Even though some airports are operating during daylight, the rule says \"limited exceptions do not disqualify a broad closure.\" So even if some airports have exceptions, if the region is covered and the suspension is broad for all commercial flights transit/arrival/departure—except those exceptions—it might qualify.\n\nHowever, the defendant points out that the NOTAM says \"all airports in west part... closed except\" which are operational. But flights transiting might still be affected because even if airports are closed, overflights may be restricted. The NOTAM says \"all airports closed,\" which likely affects both arrivals/departures and possibly overflights. But the NOTAM's wording is about airports, not the entire airspace region.\n\nBut the rule says: \"a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\" So if the closure of airports in the western part of the Tehran FIR leads to suspension of those flights, then it might qualify.\n\nLooking at the reports: Indian Express says \"suspended all civil flight permits in the western sector of the Tehran Flight Information Region (OIIX)\" and \"flights are restricted to daylight hours... rerouting away from western Iranian airspace.\"\n\nSo the sector is closed, with some exception airports. But the sector is part of the Tehran FIR. The rule says \"a major Iranian airspace region.\" The western part of Tehran FIR could be considered a major region.\n\nAlso, the market examples: April 2024 closure of Iran’s western airspace is a qualifying example. This appears similar—regional closure with some exceptions. In April 2024 case, Reuters link mentions airports canceling flights, etc.\n\nIn this case, the NOTAM's scope is \"west part of Tehran FIR,\" which seems similar to April 2024.\n\nThe issue: does \"west part of Tehran FIR\" count as a major airspace region? The rule doesn't define what's \"major,\" but the market's own example of April 2024's western closure counts as qualifying.\n\nSo the evidence shows:\n\n- Iran initiated the closure (via CAA NOTAM)\n- Non-weather cause (security context)\n- Timing through deadline\n- Scope: Western part of Tehran FIR. The NOTAM closes all airports there except some that operate daylight with approvals. The market's own examples include similar partial closures in the western region.\n\nThe rule says \"limited exceptions to a broad closure will not disqualify.\" So even with exceptions for some airports during daylight, if the overall closure is broad across the region, it qualifies.\n\nIn this case, the NOTAM states \"all airports in west part... closed except X,\" which is consistent with the \"broad closure with limited exceptions\" the rule allows. The April 2024 example was a similar regional closure (western airspace).\n\nThe defendant's argument that it's only \"airport operations\" but not airspace closure may not be relevant. The rule is about commercial flights transiting, arriving, departing from the airspace region. If airports in the region are closed for commercial flights, that would mean those flights are suspended. The NOTAM's language is about airport closure, but in practice, that's how airspace closures are managed—closing airports implies restricting the airspace.\n\nGiven that the market includes April 2024 western closure as a qualifying example, and this case's closure is similar in scope (western part of Tehran FIR with exceptions), it seems to meet the standard.\n\nAlso, the primary resolution sources are official Iranian aviation and credible reporting. The NOTAM is from CAA via Notamify, corroborated by Indian Express and Arab Times. Notamify is a third party, but the RAW NOTAM text is detailed enough.\n\nThe plaintiff's evidence shows that the closure was in force until May 25 08:30 UTC, which is past the May 24 11:59 PM ET deadline (which is May 25 03:59 UTC).\n\nSo, based on the record: yes, the proposition is demonstrated.\n\nBut wait, the defendant says that the listed airports (like Mehrabad) remain operational, so it's not a complete suspension for those. But the rule says \"for the major-region path,\" you don't need all airports closed, just a major region. The key is whether it's a broad closure of that region, with exceptions allowed.\n\nThe rule says \"limited exceptions to a broad closure will not disqualify.\" So if there's a broad closure with some exceptions (e.g., specific airports open during daylight), that's acceptable.\n\nIn the April 2024 example, there were probably similar exceptions. Reuters article for April 2024 says \"Iranian airports cancel flights until Monday morning\"—probably a temporary closure, but with exceptions as per the NOTAM.\n\nSo yes, the evidence supports that the closure was a major closure as defined.\n\nThe vote should be \"demonstrated.\"\n\nRationale needs to be concise (<=3 sentences). Let's see.\n\nPossible rationale: \"The recorded NOTAMs and corroborating reports confirm Iran initiated a regional closure of the western Tehran FIR, with limited exceptions as permitted under the market rule. The April 2024 western airspace closure is a qualifying example, and this event meets the same standard. Preponderance of evidence satisfies the 'major closure' definition for a non-weather event.\"\n\nWait, but according to the defendant's DX-S4, the market's rule says \"a broad closure... applying generally to flights across Iran or a major region.\" So \"western part of Tehran FIR\" being a major region is key.\n\nAccording to the market rule's definition, the major closure is \"a broad closure... of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region.\" So if the western part of Tehran FIR is a major region, then yes. Tehran FIR is a region in Iran's airspace.\n\nYes. The NOTAM closes all airports in west part, which would suspend commercial flights there. The rule doesn't require the entire country—just a major region. Western Tehran FIR qualifies as such.\n\nSo vote is \"demonstrated.\"\n\nRationale: \"Iran's NOTAM closed the western Tehran FIR airspace with limited exceptions as allowed by the rule, corroborated by credible reporting. The closure matches the April 2024 example cited in the market's rule. The evidence shows a regional closure meeting the preponderance standard.\"\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_0ba1a9ea7bde47f8bc606b","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Iran's NOTAM closed the western Tehran FIR airspace for commercial flights with limited exceptions permitted under the rule. This matches the April 2024 qualified example cited in the market definition. Evidence satisfies preponderance standard for a major closure.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":20337,"output":2265,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":22602,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781914308991,"responseId":"gen-1781914309-LwOAnqXUFOen4WKdAEe4","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"},{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_0ba1a9ea7bde47f8bc606b","toolName":"mcp","content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C6\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260619235218\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C6\nremaining_ms: 869177\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260619235218\",\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"text\":\"Council vote accepted.\"},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":true,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-20T00:26:35.631444415Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":869177,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":14}}"}],"details":{"mode":"call","mcpResult":{"content":[{"type":"text","text":"ok: true\nmember_id: C6\ncase_id: arb-ex11a-20260619235218\nphase: deliberation\nopportunity_id: deliberation:1:C6\nremaining_ms: 869177\nattempts_remaining: 3\njson: {\"case_id\":\"arb-ex11a-20260619235218\",\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"ok\":true,\"result\":{\"text\":\"Council vote accepted.\"},\"turn\":{\"attempts_max\":3,\"attempts_remaining\":3,\"completed\":true,\"deadline\":\"2026-06-20T00:26:35.631444415Z\",\"deliberation_round\":1,\"member_id\":\"C6\",\"opportunity_id\":\"deliberation:1:C6\",\"phase\":\"deliberation\",\"remaining_ms\":869177,\"role_id\":\"council\",\"turn_number\":14}}"}],"structuredContent":{"case_id":"arb-ex11a-20260619235218","member_id":"C6","ok":true,"result":{"text":"Council vote accepted."},"turn":{"attempts_max":3,"attempts_remaining":3,"completed":true,"deadline":"2026-06-20T00:26:35.631444415Z","deliberation_round":1,"member_id":"C6","opportunity_id":"deliberation:1:C6","phase":"deliberation","remaining_ms":869177,"role_id":"council","turn_number":14}},"isError":false},"server":"aar","tool":"submit_council_vote"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1781914326456},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Okay, the user provided a detailed case scenario where I need to act as council member C6 for AAR case arb-ex11a-20260619235218. Let me recap what happened.\n\nFirst, I called mcp with aar_wait_for_opportunity. It returned state: ready, so I proceeded to read the prompt, which outlined the case details, arguments from both plaintiff and defendant, and the evidence presented.\n\nThe main question was whether Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET. The rule defines \"major closure\" as a broad closure or suspension of commercial flights in a major airspace region, with limited exceptions allowed, or complete suspension of two listed airports.\n\nLooking at the evidence:\n- PX-2 and PX-3 are NOTAMs (A1010/26 and A1015/26) showing all airports in the western Tehran FIR were closed except specific ones operating daylight with fresh permissions. Both had timeframes covering the deadline.\n- PX-4 and PX-5 (Indian Express and Arab Times) corroborate the NOTAMs, mentioning the closure was due to security, not weather, and specific airports like Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini had restricted operations.\n\nThe defense argued that the NOTAMs are categorized as \"Airport Operations\" and don't explicitly cover transiting flights or a general suspension of all commercial flights in the region, emphasizing exceptions. However, the plaintiff pointed out that the rule allows limited exceptions and cites April 2024 western airspace closure as a qualifying example.\n\nThe market rule's qualifying example for April 2024 seems relevant here. The key is whether the western Tehran FIR closure fits as a major region. The NOTAM refers to \"west part of Tehran FIR,\" which the rule examples indicate qualifies as a major region (like the April 2024 example). The fact that multiple airports were closed with exceptions but the restriction was broadly applied, and it was officially from Iran's CAA, meets the standard.\n\nThe rationale for the vote needs to be concise. The vote should be \"demonstrated\" because:\n- Iran's NOTAM closed the western Tehran FIR airspace with limited exceptions (as per the rule's allowance for exceptions).\n- This is supported by the court's own referenced example (April 2024 closure).\n- Evidence from credible reports confirms the non-weather context and official source.\n\nSo, I called aar_submit_council_vote with vote: demonstrated and a short rationale. The response was \"Council vote accepted.\" Now, the next step is to report back that the vote was accepted and stop. Since the response included \"ok: true\" and \"Council vote accepted.\", the task is complete.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"The council vote was accepted. Vote: demonstrated. Rationale: Iran's NOTAM closed the western Tehran FIR airspace for commercial flights with limited exceptions permitted under the rule. This matches the April 2024 qualified example cited in the market definition. Evidence satisfies preponderance standard for a major closure."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":20656,"output":651,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":21307,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1781914326456,"responseId":"gen-1781914326-uUYDO1NJQdXmuUmzae9A","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}],"willRetry":false}
